	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />In addition to the connector getting dirty/corroded, it eventually gets bent out of shape from being used and that just makes any dirt even worse.  A few people have said slightly bending each of the 72 pins fixes it, I haven't tried that though.  I bought a new connector for mine, for $7 or so I think it was.
<br />
<br />This page has a walkthrough of it (mostly just taking the thing apart though, there's surely plenty of screws).  <a href="http://josh.kfoo.net/videogames/nes_repair/" class="postlink">http://josh.kfoo.net/videogames/nes_repair/</a>

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Quietust</b> [ Thu Dec 28, 2006 9:57 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />That site recommends using metal polish, both on the motherboard's edge connector (to the 72-pin connector) and on cartridges, which, <a href="http://nesdev.com/bbs/viewtopic.php?t=1203" class="postlink">as I seem to recall</a>, is probably the <em>worst</em> thing to use, since it will tend to strip off any protective coating from the connectors (i.e. tin plating on the motherboard, gold plating on the cartridges) and make them even <strong>more</strong> susceptible to corrosion.
<br />
<br />Isopropyl alcohol and cotton swabs is probably the best thing you can do for your cartridges, and cleaning the edge connector on the NES motherboard itself should be completely unnecessary since the 72-pin connector doesn't actually move around - all you need to clean (and bend pins on) is the part of the 72-pin connector that touches the cartridges.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


