	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Every system I get in now I pop open, clean the motherboard connection with a white eraser and some isopropyl alcohol, bend back the pins and I clip the lock out chip.  All of these systems run better than new, the blinking screen is completely eliminated as it is a result of the lock out chip.  I also don't push the carts down in the system as that bends the pins down much faster, meaning you'll have to go and bend the pins back that much quicker.  I just did this to one of my systems this weekend and gave it a nice black paint job to match a pair of Sharp NES TV controllers, pics are up on the technical and restoration forum over on digital press.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


